LocaLe: Milestone 1 - Neighborhood & Job Map Strategy
1) The Mission & Global Vision
LocaLe is a decentralized, peer-to-peer (P2P) marketplace designed to scale across borderless markets. Our goal is to eliminate "Trust Friction" globally using Solana-based escrow and QR-code verification. We are starting with high-friction "stress tests" in Nigeria to perfect the logic before horizontal international expansion.
2) Geographic Validation Strategy (The "Nodes")
We are validating the model across three distinct socio-economic nodes to prove the technology is adaptable to any market:
•	Node A (Owerri - FUTO/Ihiagwa Axis): High-density student market. Focus on high-frequency micro-errands and high-risk gadget repairs.
•	Node B (Lagos - Ojo/LASU Axis): High-density informal artisan market. Focus on essential home repairs and generator maintenance.
•	Node C (Lagos - Lekki Igbuefon): Premium residential market. Focus on high-value trust-dependent services like professional cleaning and smart-home setup.
3) The Role-Flex Model
LocaLe uses a fluid user architecture. There are no rigid "Buyer" or "Seller" accounts. Any user can:
•	Post a Job: Hire a neighbor for a task.
•	Accept a Job: Earn money by fulfilling a neighbor's request.
Validation will focus on the "Double-Sided Trust Pain": Hirers fear being scammed (specifically "parts-swapping"); Providers fear not being paid.
4) Core Jobs to Validate
•	High-Frequency (Low Dispute): Laundry pick-up, lodge cleaning, and errand running.
•	High-Value (Trust Dependent): Laptop/Phone repairs (focusing on the "parts-swapping" fear), electrical work, and generator maintenance.
5) Evidence of Demand (Observation-Based Validation)
Validation will be derived from digital social listening and manual concierge testing:
•	Social Listening: Monitoring active WhatsApp and Telegram "Lodge" and "Estate" groups for real-time service requests and scam complaints.
•	Direct Observation: Mapping existing informal "stands" and service clusters in the Ojo and Ihiagwa axis.
•	Concierge Testing: Manually facilitating 2–3 escrow-style trades to observe where the "Job Done" verification (QR scan) might succeed or fail.
6) Go / No-Go Signals
•	GO: If we identify at least 3 job categories with a consistent ₦5k+ price point and a repeated "Trust Pain" mentioned in community forums.
•	NO-GO: If users in these nodes express that they prefer unverified cash transactions despite the risk of scams.
7) Deliverables
•	One-Page Summary: Finalized job types and "Job Done" definitions for the three target nodes.
•	Observation Log: A summary of real-world "Pain Signals" gathered from digital community spaces.
•	Escrow Workflow: A technical logic map for the QR-release mechanism.
