PART 2

LocaLe – FUTO (Ihiagwa/Eziobodo) Observation Notes (Laundry + Gadget Repairs)
Date range: [today]
Location: Ihiagwa/Eziobodo (FUTO)
Categories observed: Laundry, Gadget Repairs (+ a bit of delivery/cleaning)
1) What I observed (the “truth”)
Laundry
•	Flow: drop-off → notebook entry → pay later
•	Failure point: post-pay ghosting ~20% (provider carries 100% risk)
Gadget repairs
•	Flow: diagnosis → parts needed → customer pays “commitment” → repair → “switch it on and see”
•	Failure point: customers withhold full payment until testing, causing technician cashflow friction
Current “job done” proof
•	Mostly informal: “switch it on and see” / physical presence / notebook tracking
2) Trust workarounds people use today
•	Post-pay (laundry): provider takes risk
•	Part-payment/commitment (repairs): risk split (approx 40/60)
•	Physical surveillance (cleaning): buyer reduces risk to near-zero
•	Blind trust (delivery): buyer takes risk (rider goes silent)
3) Micro-intercepts (quick questions) – results
Fee preference
•	Winner: ₦100 flat “Security Fee” (predictable > %)
Escrow reaction
•	Buyers: positive (“love escrow”)
•	Providers: concerned about payout delays
•	Required payout speed: < 5 minutes after QR release
4) Key insights (what this means)
•	The biggest pain is payment risk (ghosting / withholding) not “finding providers.”
•	Adoption depends on fast payout + clear completion rules.
•	Repairs need a parts-payment model (escrow must handle parts vs labor).
5) Decisions / hypotheses to test next
•	Pricing hypothesis: Start with ₦100 flat fee in pilot.
•	Payout SLA: Design/communicate payout as instant / under 5 minutes.
•	Job done rules to pilot:
•	Laundry: item count + condition check + pickup confirmation
•	Repairs: test checklist (screen/touch/camera/speaker/charging) + acceptance window
•	Repairs payment model to test: (choose one)
•	 Two-stage escrow (parts deposit + labor release)
•	 Customer buys parts directly; escrow covers labor only
6) Evidence snippets (2–4 quotes)
•	Buyer quote: “[paste exact words]”
•	Provider quote: “[paste exact words]”
7) Observed scenarios (examples)
•	Laundry drop-off: notebook tracking → post-pay risk
•	Phone repair: “₦5k screen” → ₦2k commitment → test on pickup
•	Delivery: upfront transfer → rider silent 20 mins
•	Cleaning: buyer stays present (surveillance)


LocaLe Research Notes — FUTO (Ihiagwa/Eziobodo)
Focus: Laundry + Gadget repairs
What I observed (problems):
•	Laundry: “post-pay” is common; about 20% of students ghost on payment day.
•	Repairs: students withhold full payment until they test the device, causing friction; techs need cash for parts.
Trust workarounds people use:
•	Laundry man writes names in a notebook (provider takes the risk).
•	Repairs use “commitment/part-payment” (risk split).
•	Cleaning: customer watches the cleaner (physical surveillance).
•	Delivery: buyer pays upfront and hopes (blind trust).
Current ‘job done’ proof:
•	Mostly “switch it on and see” (no formal verification).
Micro-intercepts (quick questions):
•	₦100 flat “security fee” is preferred over % fees.
•	Buyers like escrow.
•	Providers fear payout delays; payout must be under 5 minutes after QR release.
What this means for the product/pilot:
•	Start with ₦100 flat fee.
•	Build/communicate fast payout (<5 mins).
•	Create simple “job done” checklists for laundry + repairs.
•	Repairs may need two-step payment (parts deposit + labor release).

